# Pull Request Writing Guide

When an engineer asks you to help write, draft, or create a PR, follow this process.

## 1 — Read the changes first

Before writing anything, run:
- `git diff main...HEAD --stat` to see which files changed
- `git log main...HEAD --oneline` to see the commit history
- `git diff main...HEAD` to read the actual changes

Do not draft the PR until you have read the diff. The Outcome must reflect what the code actually does.

## 2 — Scope labels

Map changed files to the correct `scope:` labels. A PR can have more than one.

| Label | Applies to |
|---|---|
| `scope:fe` | Frontend, UI, web client |
| `scope:be` | Backend, API, server, services |
| `scope:ml` | ML models, inference, training pipelines |
| `scope:data` | Data pipelines, ETL, analytics, warehousing |

Adapt to this repo's actual directory structure — look at the file paths in the diff.

## 3 — Change type labels

Pick the most accurate change type. Add `change:release` alongside it if the change is customer-facing or system-impacting and should appear in the daily release notes.

| Label | Use when |
|---|---|
| `change:feat` | New capability |
| `change:fix` | Bug correction |
| `change:perf` | Measurable performance improvement |
| `change:breaking` | Non-backwards-compatible API or contract change |
| `change:refactor` | Internal restructure, no behaviour change |
| `change:chore` | Tooling, deps, CI, config |
| `change:docs` | Documentation only |
| `change:release` | Add alongside any label when this should appear in release notes |
| `change:release-ff` | Released behind a feature flag — appears in release notes marked as early access |

`change:release` and `change:release-ff` are mutually exclusive — a change is either fully live or behind a flag, not both.

## 4 — PR template

Every PR must follow this structure:

```markdown
## Summary
<!-- 1–2 sentences. What does this PR do? -->

## Outcome
<!-- Required. What is the user-facing or system impact?
     This section is pulled directly into the daily release notes that go to Slack.
     Be specific: "Forecast exports now support currency filtering, reducing payload size by 80%."
     Not: "Updated the export function." -->

## Steps to test
- [ ] Step one
- [ ] Step two

## Media
<!-- Screenshot, recording, or diagram. Write "N/A — no UI change" if not applicable. -->
```

## 5 — Title format

```
<type>: <short imperative description>
```

Examples:
- `feat: add cursor-paginated transaction export`
- `fix: prevent duplicate webhook deliveries on retry`
- `perf: cut forecast serving latency from 340ms to 42ms`
- `feat!: migrate auth to short-lived JWT tokens` ← breaking changes use `!`

## 6 — What makes a good Outcome

The Outcome section feeds directly into automated release notes. It must:
- Describe the impact to users or the system, not the implementation
- Be written in the past or present tense ("Users can now…", "The model now…", "Exports now…")
- Be specific — include numbers or comparisons where available
- Be a complete sentence, 1–3 sentences max

**Good:** "The dashboard now groups accounts by legal entity with collapsible sections, cutting scroll time by 60% for teams with 20+ accounts."

**Bad:** "Redesigned the sidebar component."

## 7 — CI requirements

The PR label check workflow will block merging if:
- No `scope:` label is present
- No `change:` label is present
- The `## Outcome` section is empty
- Both `change:release` and `change:release-ff` are applied

Confirm all four conditions are met before telling the engineer the PR is ready.
